NEW YORK -(Dow Jones)- Enron Corp. (ENE) Chairman and Chief Executive Kennet=
h Lay said the company had procedures in place to avoid conflicts of interes=
t in dealings between Enron and partnerships that were set up and run by its=
 chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow.=20
Last week, the Securities and Exchange Commission asked the Houston energy t=
rading company to provide additional information about the partnerships, whi=
ch Enron said were off-balance sheet financing vehicles used to hedge agains=
t fluctuations in the market.
In a conference call held Monday to discuss investor concerns about the SEC =
investigation and related matters, Lay said there was a "Chinese wall" in pl=
ace to protect the interest of Enron shareholders.=20
The procedures were "rigorously followed," Lay said.=20
In previous filings with the SEC, Enron said the terms of the transactions w=
ith the partnerships were "reasonable compared to those which could have bee=
n negotiated with unrelated third parties."=20
Fastow resigned from the partnerships, which were known as LJM Cayman LP and=
 LJM2 Co-Investments LP in late July.=20
The company also is involved in other off-balance sheet financing vehicles, =
including Marlin Water Trust II and Whitewing.=20
During the conference call, investors said they were frustrated by the compl=
ex nature of the trusts, and asked for more information.=20
Lay said the company would be providing a list of "Frequently Asked Question=
s" on its Web site later Tuesday that may provide more details.=20
After Enron disclosed the SEC investigation Monday, the company's stock sunk=
 to its lowest level in 52 weeks, $19.67. Enron shares were recently trading=
 up 47 cents, or 2.3%, at $21.12, in brisk volume that has already surpassed=
 its average daily turnover of 6.3 million shares.=20
Lay said he was "extremely disappointed" in the current stock price.=20
"Our businesses are performing very well and we are continuing to conduct bu=
siness," he said.=20

During the conference call, Enron officials declined to specify Fastow's rol=
e in the partnership, citing the ongoing SEC investigation and a derivative =
lawsuit filed against Enron that alleges its board breached its fiduciary du=
ties by allowing Fastow to create and run the partnerships.=20
Enron officials also addressed concerns that investors had about the potenti=
al need to issue additional Enron stock.=20
Under certain circumstances, for example, if both Enron's stock and credit r=
ating fall to certain levels, the company would need to issue additional sha=
res to the partnerships, diluting the holdings of current shareholders.=20
Enron officials declined to say how much dilution would occur under a "worst=
-case scenario."=20
However, the officials said they doubted there would be a need to issue the =
additional stock because the company plans to work with the credit-rating ag=
encies to prevent such an event.=20
Moody's put Enron on watch for a downgrade of its long-term debt last week a=
fter the company announced a $1 billion third-quarter write-off that produce=
d a $618 million loss.=20
According to Lay, Enron's debt rating would need to fall several notches to =
below investment grade in order to trigger the need to issue more stock.=20
"We are committed to maintaining our ratings," Lay said. "Moody's said they =
would work with us," he added.=20
Furthermore, Fastow said, Enron expects to have "sufficient liquidity" to me=
et all its capital requirements.=20

Enron's efforts to unwind the LJM partnerships contributed to a reduction of=
 $1.2 billion in shareholder equity. However, Enron's Lay said the lower num=
ber of shares outstanding wouldn't affect the company's earnings outlook.=20
Enron has said it expects to earn $1.80 a share in 2001 and $2.15 a share in=
 2002. The numbers are in line with the consensus estimates reported by Thom=
son Financial/First Call.=20
"Despite the economy going softer, we think we can meet that," Lay said.=20
